column5: Fuze currently powers digital asset investment infrastructure for two major UAE banks. Our platform supports KYC reliance for seamless onboarding, real-time price feeds, best execution protocols to ensure optimal pricing, and secure custody solutions. Within the first six months of launch, one in every four new users onboarded opted for digital asset investment, contributing to significant transaction volumes and client engagement.  We have also deployed a closed-loop investment infrastructure in partnership with Wio Bank and Wio Securities. In parallel, other financial institutions are implementing hybrid models—ranging from partially closed-loop to fully open-loop ecosystems—integrating features such as payment rails, card issuance, and digital asset flows.  Currently, two additional large-scale fintechs/financial institutions in the UAE are undergoing integration with our infrastructure. Their go-live is scheduled for Q2–Q3 2025.  Methodology and Implementation Timelines  Our approach is API-first, enabling seamless integration into a bank’s core systems. Each engagement is tailored to the partner's infrastructure and regulatory requirements, but typical implementation follows this phased approach:  Phase 1: Discovery & Technical Scoping (2–3 weeks)  Phase 2: API Integration & UAT (4–6 weeks)  Phase 3: Compliance Testing & Final Configuration (2 weeks)  Phase 4: Go-Live & Post-Launch Support (1–2 weeks)  Financial Stability and Insurance Coverage  Fuze maintains comprehensive insurance coverage through Marsh Insurance, including:  Professional Indemnity Insurance  Directors & Officers (D&O) Insurance  Crime Insurance  Cybersecurity Insurance  Given the nature of our business, our technology platform is the operational core. All transactions are logged, reconciliations are performed within the internal ledger system, and critical controls are implemented to ensure auditability and protection. As a result, we maintain enhanced crime and cyber risk coverage specifically tailored to our operational exposure.  We remain fully compliant with all applicable regulatory and legal requirements in the jurisdictions in which we operate.  Fuze has done over a billion USD in FY 2024 and achieved EBITDA profitability. With the growth trajectory Fuze will grow by 5-8x maintaining its profitability. The parent entity continues to support its subsidiaries Fuze raised $14M in its pre-seed round in 2023 and still has a healthy balance sheet that can support operations for the next 2 years.

column2: Has your company been compliant with all applicable legal and regulatory requirements over the past years?
column3: Please share your company Third-party risk management policy  Please share your company procedure to manage risk associated with your subcontractors. Please share internal or external audit report focusing on compliance with legal and regulatory changes.
column5: Yes, Fuze remains compliant with all applicable legal and regulatory requirements since being licensed and regulated by the Virtual Assets Regulatory Authority ("VARA") in Dubai.  As a regulated Virtual Asset Service Provider, we have established a comprehensive compliance framework aligned with VARA’s Rulebooks, FATF recommendations, and broader local and international regulatory expectations.  Fuze has a comprehensive Outsourcing Policy in place, which effectively covers Third-Party Risk Management to manage and mitigate risks associated with subcontractors and vendors throughout the lifecycle of the engagement. The policy addresses critical areas of risk, including data security, intellectual property protection, and regulatory compliance, with appropriate safeguards and controls in place.   The third party / vendor onboarding process is designed to mitigate risks before engagement begins, including reputational, operational, legal, and financial risks. This involves conducting thorough due diligence and risk assessments, and incorporating contractual safeguards such as dispute resolution mechanisms, termination rights, and compliance requirements. It also ensures that vendors are aligned with our internal risk appetite and meet the expectations of relevant stakeholders.  Once a third party / vendor is onboarded, ongoing monitoring is critical to ensure continued compliance and performance. We conduct regular evaluations against agreed service-level agreements (SLAs) and key performance indicators (KPIs), and perform periodic risk reviews to assess any changes in the vendor’s risk profile. This process helps ensure that vendors are able to evolve alongside our business and continue to meet our operational and strategic needs.  The framework is led by the Head of Risk, who reports directly to the Board and administratively to the CEO.   The Risk Function will produce regular risk reports for senior management and the Board. Additionally, risk oversight is conducted by the Audit, Risk, and Compliance Committee (ARCC) which ensures independent scrutiny of all risk activities and escalates findings to the Board.  Fuze operates a Three Lines of Defence model:  - First Line: Risk ownership by business and operational units - Second Line: Independent risk oversight by the Risk Function - Third Line: Independent controls testing and assurance provided by Internal Audit  Audit and Regulatory Compliance Internal audits are conducted periodically to assess the effectiveness of our risk controls, compliance with legal and regulatory obligations, and operational resilience. These audits are aligned with industry standards and overseen by the ARCC.  We are happy to share a summary of our most recent internal audit reports under NDA, focusing on compliance with applicable laws and regulatory changes.

Our internal control environment is structured to ensure the integrity of operations, compliance with applicable legal and regulatory requirements, and effective mitigation of key risks across the business.   These controls are embedded within our day-to-day processes and are subject to periodic review and enhancement based on risk assessments, audit findings, and regulatory developments.  Our risk management practices is led by our dedicated Head of Risk, and are governed by a documented Risk Management Policy and Framework, which defines our approach to: - Identifying, assessing, and mitigating operational, compliance, financial, technology, and third-party risks - Assigning clear ownership of risks and controls across the first and second lines of defence - Maintaining a risk register and conducting periodic risk reviews - Ensuring escalation protocols are in place for material risks or control breaches In addition, our internal control environment includes: - Defined roles and responsibilities with appropriate segregation of duties - Policies and procedures across key risk areas (e.g., AML/CFT, cybersecurity, business continuity) - Regular compliance monitoring and internal testing programs (as part of our compliance monitoring programme) - Internal audits to validate control effectiveness

Does your organization maintain, and implement policies and procedures to protect personal information?
column3: Please share the policies related to protection of personal information
column5: At Fuze, we are committed to safeguarding the personal information of our clients and their customers. We implement a comprehensive, multi-layered security approach to ensure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of sensitive data. Key measures include:  End-to-End Encryption: All data transmitted between our platform and users is secured with industry-standard encryption protocols (e.g., TLS/SSL), ensuring that sensitive information remains protected from unauthorized access during transmission.  Data-at-Rest Encryption: Fuze encrypts all stored data, including transaction records and personal information, using robust encryption algorithms to prevent unauthorized access to sensitive data.  Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA): We enforce MFA for all users accessing our platform, adding an extra layer of security beyond passwords to help prevent unauthorized access, even if user credentials are compromised.  Role-Based Access Control (RBAC): Fuze implements RBAC, limiting access to sensitive information and functionalities based on defined user roles. This ensures that only authorized personnel have access to critical data and systems.  Intrusion Detection and Prevention Systems (IDS/IPS): Our systems continuously monitor network traffic to detect and prevent unauthorized access or malicious activities in real time.  Security Information and Event Management (SIEM): Fuze utilizes SIEM tools across all hosts, cloud services, and critical infrastructure, ensuring continuous monitoring, profiling, and analysis of events and logs generated by our systems.  Regular Vulnerability Assessments and Penetration Testing (VAPT): We conduct VAPT exercises every six months to identify and address security vulnerabilities proactively. This is complemented by routine security audits to ensure compliance with industry standards.  Secure Wallet Management: Fuze employs a multi-custody solution for managing digital assets, utilizing both hot and cold wallets. Cold wallets, disconnected from the internet, offer an additional layer of protection against online threats.  Compliance with Industry Standards: Fuze adheres to international security standards, including SOC 2 Type II, ISO 27001, and NESA, ensuring our data protection practices align with the highest industry benchmarks.  Smart Contract Security: All smart contracts deployed on our platform undergo rigorous security audits and reviews to identify and mitigate potential vulnerabilities before deployment.  Continuous Monitoring and Incident Response: Our dedicated security team constantly monitors system activities for suspicious behavior and potential threats. In the event of a security incident, our team is prepared to respond promptly to minimize any potential impact.  User Privacy Protection: Fuze ensures compliance with global data privacy regulations, including GDPR and UAE data protection laws, by limiting access to personal and financial data to authorized personnel only and safeguarding it in accordance with these regulations.  These security measures, backed by a strong governance framework, protect both our clients and their customers from evolving digital security threats.

column2: Is your organization IT infrastructure adequate to support the services required?
column3: Please share your company Information Security Policy Share certifications related SOC2 Evidence of compliance with relevant industry standards and regulations such as GDPR etc
column5: Overview of Fuze's Current System Architecture/Infrastructure:  Fuze’s system architecture is designed to meet the scalability, flexibility, and security requirements needed to support our services, while ensuring compliance with industry standards, including GDPR and other data protection regulations. Our infrastructure leverages cloud-based solutions from trusted industry providers to guarantee high availability, reliability, and rapid scaling.  Cloud Providers and Locations: Fuze utilizes AWS cloud infrastructure, primarily hosted in the me-central-1 region of AWS. This setup complies with UAE data protection laws and incorporates geographic redundancy and high availability across multiple Availability Zones (AZs). By employing this configuration, we ensure seamless operations even during disruptions while adhering to the highest standards of data security and privacy, including compliance with GDPR for EU-based customers.  Service Providers: Fuze integrates with key service providers to support our security and compliance requirements, including:  Fireblocks for custody services  Chainalysis for compliance  Notabene for Travel Rule compliance  Our platform’s architecture is flexible, supporting multiple custody providers, Travel Rule providers, and KYT/AML solutions, which allows us to offer scalable and adaptable solutions that meet the dynamic needs of our clients and regulatory standards.  Tech Stack: Fuze is built on a microservices-based architecture with a modular approach, enabling flexibility and ease of scaling. Our system is event-driven, utilizing a Pub/Sub mechanism to ensure efficient horizontal and vertical scaling. Key technologies include:  SOR and OEMS: Fuze uses an inbuilt and proprietary Order Execution Management System (OEMS) and Smart Order Routing (SOR), optimizing trade execution by considering factors like price, slippage, and volume.  APIs: We utilize REST APIs and WebSockets for real-time communication and trading.  Databases: Fuze employs high-performance databases, including PostgreSQL for transactional data, DynamoDB for high-availability document storage, and Influx for timeseries storage.  Security: Our platform integrates end-to-end encryption, multi-factor authentication (MFA), and a suite of security tools such as SIEM, IDS, and IPS to ensure comprehensive security throughout our infrastructure.  Disaster Recovery: Fuze has implemented a robust disaster recovery plan, with automatic failover and backup systems in place across multiple Availability Zones to prevent data loss. We conduct quarterly disaster recovery tests to ensure the readiness of our plan in case of critical incidents. A Business Continuity Planning (BCP) cluster is also in place to ensure continuity of operations should AWS become unavailable in the UAE.  Utilization of Smart Contracts: Smart contracts are utilized within our system for both custody and asset management, ensuring that digital assets are locked, transferred, or released only when predefined criteria are met. This provides enhanced security and ensures compliance with both internal policies and regulatory standards, including GDPR in relation to data handling.  Custody and Asset Management: Digital asset custody is managed through smart contracts, ensuring that the assets are secured and only accessible under specified conditions.  Tokenized Assets: We support the integration of tokenized real-world assets (e.g., real estate or commodities) via smart contracts, facilitating seamless and transparent transfers on the blockchain.  GDPR Compliance: Fuze is committed to maintaining the highest levels of data protection for all personal information under our control. Our infrastructure is designed with GDPR compliance in mind, ensuring that personal data is processed lawfully, transparently, and for specified purposes only. We have implemented strong security measures, including encryption, role-based access controls, and regular audits, to protect data privacy. Additionally, we ensure that data subjects’ rights, such as access, rectification, erasure, and data portability, are respected in line with GDPR requirements.  This architecture, coupled with our strict compliance to GDPR and other international standards, ensures that Fuze can deliver secure, scalable, and efficient services while upholding the highest levels of compliance and data privacy.

Key security and privacy practices include:  Data Encryption: All data is encrypted both in transit and at rest, ensuring protection from unauthorized access.  Access Controls: We implement Role-Based Access Control (RBAC), ensuring that only authorized personnel have access to sensitive data based on defined roles and responsibilities.  Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA): MFA is enforced for all users accessing our platform, adding an extra layer of security to prevent unauthorized access.  Data Minimization: We ensure that only the minimum necessary data is collected, stored, and processed, in line with GDPR principles.  Incident Response and Monitoring: We have a dedicated team that continuously monitors system activity for suspicious behavior, ensuring swift response to potential security incidents.  Regular Audits: Our security infrastructure undergoes regular audits and assessments, including penetration testing and vulnerability assessments, to identify and address potential weaknesses.  Employee Training: All employees undergo mandatory training on data privacy and security policies, ensuring they are fully aware of their responsibilities in protecting sensitive data.  These measures are documented in our Information Security Management System (ISMS) and regularly reviewed to ensure that they remain effective and aligned with evolving security standards and regulations.

column2: Do you have environment segregation (Chinese wall) to assure our data is not exposed to any other customers of yours or unauthorized users ?, if yes please explain how.
column3: Detailed explanation by service provider
column5: Yes, Fuze implements environment segregation to ensure that your data is not exposed to other customers or unauthorized users.  Fuze supports both logical and physical segregation of data. Protection measures are in place to prevent unauthorized access or tampering, including Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and Access Control Lists (ACLs). RBAC is enforced through our Single Sign-On (SSO) provider, ensuring that only users with the necessary permissions can access protected resources as defined in their ACL.  Additionally, all access to critical systems is governed by Fuze’s Zero Trust Security Model, which enforces RBAC at the DNS level and utilizes ACLs to ensure that only authorized personnel can access servers and sensitive data.

The following measures are in place to ensure the security of this sensitive information:  Connectivity Protected by a Firewall/VPN: All connectivity to your environment is protected by robust firewall and VPN solutions, ensuring that only authorized traffic is allowed and preventing unauthorized access to your systems.  Rules Restricted on a Need-to-Have Basis: Access control rules are strictly enforced on a need-to-have basis. Only authorized personnel with specific roles and requirements can access sensitive resources, ensuring that data and systems remain secure.  Encrypted Communication: Communication is encrypted using VPN or other industry-standard encryption mechanisms. This ensures that all data transferred between systems is secure and protected from unauthorized access during transmission.  These measures are part of our comprehensive security framework to protect your data and ensure that credentials shared with us remain secure throughout our engagement.

column5: Yes, if we receive Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and sensitive data as part of this engagement, it will be stored and processed in accordance with our robust data protection protocols.  All sensitive data will be stored within our cloud infrastructure, primarily hosted in the AWS me-central-1 region in the UAE. This setup ensures compliance with UAE data protection laws and other applicable regulations.  The process for storing sensitive data includes:  Encryption at Rest and in Transit: All sensitive data is encrypted both during transmission and while stored. We utilize industry-standard encryption protocols, such as TLS/SSL for data in transit and strong encryption algorithms for data at rest.  Access Control: Sensitive data is accessible only to authorized personnel, governed by Role-Based Access Control (RBAC). This ensures that only individuals with the appropriate permissions can access or process the data.  Data Minimization: We follow the principle of data minimization, collecting and retaining only the minimum amount of sensitive data required for the engagement.  Regular Audits and Monitoring: Our systems undergo regular security audits and real-time monitoring to detect and prevent unauthorized access, ensuring the protection of sensitive data.  We also comply with relevant data privacy laws such as GDPR and UAE data protection laws, which guide our processes for the collection, storage, and processing of PII and sensitive data.

column2: Is there a set of policies and procedures that address Anti-Money Laundering obligations?
column3: Please share prevention of fraud and corruption related policies
column5: Yes, Fuze has a comprehensive set of policies and procedures in place to address Anti-Money Laundering (AML) obligations. These policies are aligned with UAE regulations and global standards, including FATF guidelines.  Our AML framework includes: - Customer Due Diligence (CDD) and Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD) based on risk classification. - Ongoing monitoring of transactions to detect and report suspicious activity. - Integration with leading compliance tools such as Chainalysis and Notabene for real-time monitoring, screening, and Travel Rule compliance. - Mandatory AML training for all relevant staff to ensure awareness and compliance. - Reporting obligations to the UAE Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU), and to VARA, as and when applicable.  These measures ensure that Fuze remains fully compliant with AML regulations and helps mitigate financial crime risks throughout the engagement.  Fuze has robust fraud and corruption prevention policies in place. We enforce clear segregation of duties and strong access controls to prevent fraud and misuse of assets, and we place the highest importance on protecting both our assets and our clients' assets against theft, fraud, and misappropriation.   Fuze leverages advanced fraud detection systems that actively monitor for suspicious activities, with any unusual behavior triggering immediate investigation. Employees undergo regular training on fraud prevention and are fully aware of their responsibility to report any suspicious activity.   Additionally, Fuze maintains a strict Anti-Bribery and Anti-Corruption Policy, which prohibits any form of bribery, kickbacks, or unethical influence, and reinforces our commitment to integrity and transparency in all business dealings.

column2: Does your company have a documented internal control environment and risk management practice?
column3: Please share the operational risk assessment procedure to identify and assess threats and vulnerabilities in a timely manner and to the extent possible, prevent them from affecting critical operations delivery.
column5: Yes, Fuze has a well-documented internal control environment and a comprehensive risk management framework aligned with regulatory expectations and global best practices.   Fuze’s operational risk assessment procedure is grounded in the Operational Risk Management Policy, which reflects Fuze’s commitment to a systematic, dynamic, and comprehensive approach to managing operational risks.   The policy outlines a multi-faceted framework designed to identify, assess, manage, and mitigate operational risks. It ensures that risks are addressed proactively to maintain operational resilience and service excellence.  To reduce the likelihood of operational risk incidents and limit their potential impact, we have implemented a range of robust measures and controls. These include: - Advanced security systems to protect digital assets and prevent unauthorized access - The use of blockchain analytics tools such as Chainalysis to monitor transactions and detect suspicious activities - Audits and inspections are conducted to ensure compliance with internal standards and regulatory requirements - Clear segregation of duties and strong access controls to prevent fraud and misuse of assets.   To ensure business continuity in the event of a disruption, we maintain comprehensive data backup and disaster recovery plans.  In addition to preventive controls, we have a clearly defined incident management and response process to minimize the impact of any operational risk event and to prevent recurrence. All employees are required to report any incidents they observe or become aware of immediately. Once reported, the Head of Risk, together with relevant departments, will investigate the incident to determine its root cause and assess its impact. Based on the findings, mitigation actions will be implemented to address the issue and prevent similar incidents in the future.

column2: Do you have a documented business continuity and disaster recovery plan?
column3: Please share copy of Business Continuity policy/framework
column5: Yes, Fuze maintains a documented and regularly tested Business Continuity Plan (BCP) and Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) to ensure the continuity of critical services and minimize operational disruptions.

column2: Is this plan tested and updated at least annually?
column3: Please share copy of Business Continuity policy/framework
column5: Yes, Fuze’s Business Continuity Plan (BCP) and Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) are tested and updated at least annually. In addition to the annual review, we conduct quarterly disaster recovery tests to ensure the effectiveness and readiness of our systems and procedures.  These exercises validate our recovery capabilities, simulate real-world failure scenarios, and help identify any areas of improvement. Following each test, results are documented, reviewed by senior management, and incorporated into our continuous improvement process.  This disciplined approach ensures that our resilience strategies remain aligned with evolving business needs, regulatory requirements, and industry best practices.

column2: Is there an alternative arrangement in place to account for unavailability of key vendors your organization relies on to provide services to Mashreq.
column3: Please share copy of Business Continuity policy/framework
column5: Yes, Fuze has alternative arrangements in place to mitigate the risk of unavailability of key vendors critical to service delivery. This includes:  Vendor Redundancy: Where feasible, Fuze maintains multiple providers for critical services such as custody, travel rule compliance, and KYT/AML monitoring. Our modular architecture allows for rapid switching between providers with minimal disruption.  Exit and Substitution Clauses: All key vendor contracts include provisions for continuity, including exit and substitution clauses to enable swift transition in the event of vendor failure.  Business Continuity Integration: Third-party risk is integrated into our Business Continuity Plan, and critical vendors are subject to periodic risk assessments and contingency planning.  Technical Flexibility: Our platform supports a plug-and-play model, allowing alternative vendors or services to be onboarded quickly to ensure uninterrupted service.  These measures ensure that Mashreq’s services are not adversely impacted in the event of third-party disruptions.

column2: Are critical third parties of your organization included in Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery testing?
column3: Please share copy of Business Continuity policy/framework
column5: Yes, critical third parties are included in our Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery testing, as explicitly outlined in the scope of applicability within our policy, and periodic testing and validation exercises are conducted to ensure the effectiveness of recovery procedures.

column2: Do you have mechanism for Handling Customer Grievances?
column5: Yes, Fuze has a documented and structured mechanism for handling customer grievances. Our grievance redressal process is designed to ensure that all customer concerns are acknowledged, investigated, and resolved in a timely and transparent manner. Key components include:  Dedicated Support Channels: Customers can raise concerns through email, phone, or our in-app support system. Each grievance is logged and tracked through a centralized case management system.  Acknowledgement and Response SLAs: Grievances are acknowledged within 24 hours, with resolution timelines governed by pre-defined service level agreements (SLAs) based on severity and complexity.  Escalation Matrix: An escalation framework is in place to ensure unresolved issues are promptly addressed by senior management.  Root Cause Analysis and Continuous Improvement: We conduct root cause analysis for critical complaints and integrate findings into our product and process improvement cycles.  Regulatory Compliance: Our grievance mechanism complies with the guidelines issued by regulatory authorities such as VARA and ensures customer protection in line with industry best practices.  This structured approach helps us maintain a high standard of customer satisfaction and accountability.

column2: Do you have a documented process for issue escalation and resolution?
column3: Please share documented process for issue escalation and resolution
column5: Yes, Fuze has a clearly defined and documented process for issue escalation and resolution to ensure timely handling of operational, technical, or service-related matters.  Key elements of the process include:  Tiered Escalation Levels: Issues are categorized by severity and are escalated through a structured hierarchy—starting from frontline support to functional heads and, if required, to executive management.  Defined SLAs: Each escalation tier is governed by predefined Service Level Agreements (SLAs) to ensure timely acknowledgment, response, and resolution.  Incident Logging & Tracking: All issues are logged in our internal case management system for tracking, accountability, and audit purposes.  Cross-Functional Coordination: For complex issues, cross-functional teams are engaged to facilitate root cause analysis and rapid resolution.  Regular Reviews and Reporting: Issue trends and resolution performance are reviewed periodically by senior management to improve system and process robustness.  This structured escalation framework ensures transparency, accountability, and prompt resolution of issues in line with best practices and regulatory expectations.

column2: Does your organization implemented a policy and supporting security measures to protect personal information accessed, processed, or stored at teleworking sites?
column5: Yes, Fuze is committed to ensuring the security and privacy of personal information, including when accessed, processed, or stored at teleworking sites. As a broker-dealer regulated by the Virtual Asset Regulatory Authority (VARA), we adhere to the Federal Decree-Law No. 45 of 2021 on the Protection of Personal Data (PDPL 2021) and relevant VARA regulations. Our Data Protection Policy outlines the comprehensive measures in place to secure personal data in line with these legal obligations.  To protect personal data from unauthorized access, disclosure, alteration, or destruction, we implement robust technical and organizational security controls. This includes: - encrypted connections for remote access - endpoint protection - secure data storage environments  Access to personal data is strictly limited to authorized personnel on a need-to-know basis, and employees are regularly trained on data privacy and security practices to reinforce our commitment to safeguarding client information.  Data stored at teleworking sites is subject to the same security standards as on-premise environments, with regular backups created to prevent data loss.  In addition, our technology governance and risk assessment framework is designed to comply, to the extent applicable, with relevant cybersecurity laws, regulatory requirements, and industry guidelines. This includes compliance with the electronic security standards adopted by the Dubai Electronic Security Center under Dubai Law No. 9 of 2022 regulating the provision of digital services in Dubai. We also ensure adherence to Federal-Decree Law No. 45 of 2021 on the Protection of Personal Data and its executive regulations, as well as any cybersecurity mandates issued by the Federal Data Office. Furthermore, our practices align with the Consumer Protection Regulation issued pursuant to Central Bank Notice No. 444 of 2021, and any additional cybersecurity requirements as may be introduced by the Central Bank of the UAE.  Fuze has appointed a Data Protection Officer (DPO) to oversee the implementation of the Data Protection Policy, ensure compliance with the PDPL 2021 and act as a primary point of contact for data subjects and relevant authorities regarding data protection matters.

column2: Do you perform background verification for new hires (on-roll and third-party employees)?
column3: Please share Background Verification (BGV) process and sample BGV Verification
column5: Yes, Fuze performs comprehensive background verification for all new hires, including both on-roll employees and third-party contractors.  The verification process includes: - Identity Verification - Educational Qualification Check - Employment History Validation - Criminal Record Check (where permitted by law) - Sanctions and Watchlist Screening  These checks are conducted either in-house or via a certified background verification agency and are aligned with local labor laws and industry best practices. Verification results are documented and retained as part of the employee onboarding records.
